"1025–Deceased","1014–Male":"1014–Deceased","1040–1086":"1040–1086","1025–Female":"1025–Deceased","1025":"1025","1014":"1014","1035":"1035","1066":"1066","1086":"1086","1040":"1040","Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, England","Normandie, Charente-Maritime, Poitou-Charentes, France":"Normandie, Charente-Maritime, Poitou-Charentes, France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Richardson","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: patronymic from the Middle English personal name   Richard   + <i>-son</i>. This surname is also very common among African Americans. Compare   Ritson  .","Americanized form (and a Swedish variant) of Swedish <b>Richardsson</b> or <b>Rikardsson</b>: patronymic from the personal name   Richard  , <i>Rikard</i>.","Americanized form of Norwegian and Danish <b>Richardsen</b> or Norwegian <b>Rikardsen</b>, cognates of 2 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Richarson","meanings":["English: variant of   Richardson  ."]},{"name":"Richerson","meanings":["Probably an altered form of   Richardson   or perhaps a patronymic from   Richer  ."]},{"name":"Richard","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Armand, Emile, Jacques, Andre, Marcel, Pierre, Leonce, Normand, Camille, Lucien, Gilles, Henri.","English, French, West Indian (mainly Haiti), German, and Dutch: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>rīc</i> ‘power(ful)’ + <i>hard</i> ‘hardy, brave, strong’. The Middle English forms were <i>Richard</i> and <i>Rikard</i>, respectively Parisian Old French and Old Picard pronunciations of the ancient Germanic name. Middle English <i>Rikard</i> gives rise to the pet form   Rick  , whilst <i>Richard</i> has given the pet forms   Richie   and   Rich  . Both produced rhyming pet forms,   Dick   and   Hick   for <i>Rikard</i> and   Hitch   for <i>Richard</i>.","History: The LA Richard families are mainly descended from Acadian refugees in the second half of the 18th century. — This surname is listed in the register of Huguenot ancestors recognized by the Huguenot Society of America."]},{"name":"Richeson","meanings":["Probably an altered form of   Richardson  , but compare   Richerson  ."]},{"name":"Ritson","meanings":["English:","variant of <b>Richson</b>, a shortened form of   Richardson  . The name may sometimes have been confused with or assimilated to   Rushton  .","in southern England perhaps a habitational name from Ritson, in Halwell (Devon)."]}]},{"name":"Ruby","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the vocabulary word for the gemstone (Latin <i>rubinus</i>, from <i>rubeus</i> ‘red’). The name was chiefly common in the late 19th century and up to the middle of the 20th, and is presently enjoying a revival in parts of the English-speaking world."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705181,"age":10,"year":"1035","julianDay":2099086,"title":"England Divided","description":"King Canute died in 1035 and England was divided between his three sons. His son Sweyn received Norway, Harthacanute received Denmark, and Harold Harefoot received North England.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705182,"age":41,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705183,"age":61,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Ruby Richardson was born in 1025, in Nottinghamshire, England. She had at least 1 son with Clarion I de Marcham. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"1025–":"1025–Surnud","1014–Male":"1014–Surnud","1040–1086":"1040–1086","1025–Female":"1025–Surnud","1025":"1025","1014":"1014","1035":"1035","1066":"1066","1086":"1086","1040":"1040","Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, England","Normandie, Charente-Maritime, Poitou-Charentes, France":"Normandie, Charente-Maritime, Poitou-Charentes, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"1025–":"1025–Kuollut","1014–Male":"1014–Kuollut","1040–1086":"1040–1086","1025–Female":"1025–Kuollut","1025":"1025","1014":"1014","1035":"1035","1066":"1066","1086":"1086","1040":"1040","Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, England","Normandie, Charente-Maritime, Poitou-Charentes, France":"Normandie, Charente-Maritime, Poitou-Charentes, Ranska"},"fr":{"1025–":"1025–Décédée","1014–Male":"1014–Décédé","1040–1086":"1040–1086","1025–Female":"1025–Décédée","1025":"1025","1014":"1014","1035":"1035","1066":"1066","1086":"1086","1040":"1040","Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, Angleterre","Normandie, Charente-Maritime, Poitou-Charentes, France":"Normandie, Charente-Maritime, Poitou-Charentes, France","lifeSummary":"Ruby Richardson est née en 1025, à Nottinghamshire, Angleterre. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec Clarion I de Marcham. Elle est décédée dans sa ville natale."},"de":{"1025–":"1025–Verstorben","1014–Male":"1014–Verstorben","1040–1086":"1040–1086","1025–Female":"1025–Verstorben","1025":"1025","1014":"1014","1035":"1035","1066":"1066","1086":"1086","1040":"1040","Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottinghamshire, England","Normandie, Charente-Maritime, Poitou-Charentes, France":"Normandie, Charente-Maritime, Poitou-C